Kenneth Brown lost it all when he was sent to prison for an arson in 1996. His wife and kids, the housebroken dog, the vacation home on Cape Cod all vanished. Brown was convicted of arson and sentenced to 20 years in prison. He is currently serving his sentence in a Georgia prison.The American Correctional Chaplains Association provides programs to inmates. "It's a break from all the hustle and noise of the prison environment," says spokesman Gary Friedman. "Mostly, the people in Buddhist community are going into the prisons, providing programs," he says.Buddhism is the third most popular religion in America behind Christianity and Judaism. About 1.7 million Americans call themselves Buddhists, and many of them are converts. According to the American Religious Identification Survey in 2008, there were 1.2 million self-identified Buddhists.In California, a state where the swollen prison population has resulted in dangerously overcrowded prisons, teaching conflict management is critical, says Zen Buddhist instructor. Anne Seisen Saunders, who was raised Christian, teaches conflict management in California prisons. She says conflict management can help reduce prison overcrowding.